questions.explanation:
Hyperalgesia is an exaggerated response to a noxious stimulus. • Hyperalgesia and allodynia signify increased sensitivity of nociceptive afferent fibers. • Causes of hyperalgesia • The excessive sensitivity of the pain receptors, which is called primary hyperalgesia • Facilitation of sensory transmission, which is called secondary hyperalgesia. An example of primary hyperalgesia is the extreme sensitivity of sunburned skin, which results 
from sensitization of the skin pain endings, by local tissue products from the burn — histamine, 
prostaglandins, and others. Secondary hyperalgesia frequently results from lesions in the spinal cord or the thalamus.
